Sure! Here's a simple implementation of the selection sort algorithm in Java:

public class SelectionSortExample {
    public static void selectionSort(int[] arr) {
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length - 1; i++) {
            int index = i;
            for (int j = i + 1; j < arr.length; j++) {
                if (arr[j] < arr[index]) {
                    index = j; // searching for the lowest index
                }
            }
            int smallerNumber = arr[index];
            arr[index] = arr[i];
            arr[i] = smallerNumber;
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr1 = {9, 14, 3, 2, 43, 11, 58, 22};
        System.out.println("Before Selection Sort");
        for (int i : arr1) {
            System.out.print(i + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();

        selectionSort(arr1); // sorting array using selection sort

        System.out.println("After Selection Sort");
        for (int i : arr1) {
            System.out.print(i + " ");
        }
    }
}

### How It Works
1. **Initialization**: The algorithm starts by assuming the first element is the smallest.
2. **Finding the Minimum**: It then iterates through the array to find the smallest element.
3. **Swapping**: Once the smallest element is found, it is swapped with the first element.
4. **Repeat**: This process is repeated for the next element until the entire array is sorted.
